      <bioghist id="aspace_4abb266c494573b33ff0747e3c92e156">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Matthew Shepperson (1785-1874) was born in Norfolk, England, and attained moderate success as a portrait painter and copyist. Shepperson exhibited paintings at the Royal Academy between 1811 and 1821, and as a native of Norfolk, at the Norwich Society of Artists. As a portraitist at Buckingham Palace, he worked for both King George IV and King William IV. Additionally, he painted copies of portraits in his own collection, winning the silver medal by the Royal Academy for 'the best Copy made with the School of Painting.' He often sold these copies to numerous lords, ladies, bishops and earls.</p>
         <p>Shepperson also taught painting in circles of nobility, mainly to socially prominent young ladies. Between 1823 and 1824 he made a copy of John Hoppner's painting of Horatio Nelson, which is now in the collections of the National Maritime Museum and in 1828 he painted a portrait of John Childs of Bungay (b. 1784), his brother-in-law and member of the firm of printers Brightly &amp; Childs.</p>
         <p>Little is known regarding his personal life. He married Emma Brightly (1788-1869) on March 25, 1813. They were together until her death in 1869. Shepperson died several years later in October 1874.</p>
         <p>In August 2010, some of the paintings from Matthew  Shepperson's collection (bequeathed to his heirs) were sold at auction; the lots included Velazquez's 'Portrait of a Gentleman', which sold for £3 million.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_ce9b2e087c14182f7fc9d05131e4b94a">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>The collection comprises manuscript material concerning Matthew Shepperson's daily activties. It contains correspondence including extensive writing with his brother-in-law John Childs, account books which record forty-three years of financial records, and additional documents such as visiting cards, a receipt for paintings, and a copy of his mother's will.</p>
      </scopecontent>
